docs.abstract: As big tech companies continue to assert their influence, a handful of businesses are dominating both in sales and on Wall Street.

docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — On Monday, Amazon.com’s share price briefly crossed the $1,000 mark for the first time in its 20-year history as a publicly traded company.

headline.main: A Price Amazon Is Content to Keep High: $1,000 a Share
headline.print_headline: Amazon’s Shares Briefly Surpass $1,000, Reflecting Its Power and Potential

docs.abstract: After crushing the independent bookstore industry, Amazon opens its own. Leave your cash at home.
docs.snippet: After crushing the independent bookstore industry, Amazon opens its own. Leave your cash at home.
docs.lead_paragraph: A non-virtual, real-life Amazon bookstore opened in Manhattan on Thursday with no obvious signs of corporate guilt at having driven countless independent bookstores to oblivion with the scythe-like power of the company’s e-book discounting.

headline.main: At Amazon’s Bookstore, No Coffee but All the Data You Can Drink
headline.print_headline: At Amazon’s New Bookstore, No Coffee but All the Data You Can Drink

docs.abstract: Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Facebook and Google dominate our day-to-day activities. Imagining being forced to give up some of them could lead to hard choices.
docs.snippet: Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Facebook and Google dominate our day-to-day activities. Imagining being forced to give up some of them could lead to hard choices.
docs.lead_paragraph: A few weeks ago, I bought a new television. When the whole process was over, I realized something incredible: To navigate all of the niggling details surrounding this one commercial transaction — figuring out what to buy, which accessories I needed, how and where to install it, and whom to hire to do so — I had dealt with only a single ubiquitous corporation: Amazon.

headline.main: Tech’s Frightful Five: They’ve Got Us
headline.print_headline: Which Tech Overlords Can You Live Without?

docs.abstract: At physical bookstores like the new one opening in Manhattan this week, the company is drawing on its vast troves of customer data to shape the design.

docs.lead_paragraph: Jeff Bezos, the chief executive of Amazon, has often struck a defiant tone when asked about the company’s dominance of the book industry.

headline.main: Amazon Sets Up Shop in the Heart of the Publishing Industry
headline.print_headline: The Amazon That Readers Can Walk Into

docs.abstract: The new F.C.C. chairman’s plan to slacken net neutrality rules is a boon to tech giants and a bane to competitors and innovators.

docs.lead_paragraph: Every year, the internet gets a little less fair. The corporations that run it get a little bigger, their power grows more concentrated, and a bit of their idealism gives way to ruthless pragmatism.

headline.main: Giving the Behemoths a Leg Up on the Little Guy

docs.abstract: Tech firms are in a race to dominate consumers’ digital lives, and their services increasingly overlap each other. The convergence helps customers.
docs.snippet: Tech firms are in a race to dominate consumers’ digital lives, and their services increasingly overlap each other. The convergence helps customers.
docs.lead_paragraph: There is a growing drumbeat that the five leading tech behemoths have turned into dangerous monopolies that stifle innovation and harm consumers. Apple, Alphabet, Microsoft, Amazon and Facebook — what the tech columnist Farhad Manjoo calls the Frightful Five — have a combined market capitalization of more than $2.7 trillion and are an increasing part of everyday life.

headline.main: The ‘Frightful Five’ Aren’t So Scary, as Long as They’re Competing
